{"id":"2106.10205","submitter":"Gabriel Landi Dr.","authors":"Andr\\'e M. Timpanaro, Giacomo Guarnieri and Gabriel T. Landi","title":"The most precise quantum thermoelectric","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Thermodynamic Uncertainty Relations (TURs) place lower bounds on the\nnoise-to-signal ratio (precision) of currents in nanoscale devices. Originally\nformulated for classical time-homogeneous Markov processes, these relations,\ncan be violated in quantum-coherent devices. However, the extent to which these\nmay occur still represent a missing piece of the puzzle. In this Letter we\nprovide the definitive answer for the class of quantum thermoelectric devices\noperating in the steady-state regime. Using coherent scattering theory beyond\nlinear response, together with analytical optimization techniques, we\nrigorously prove that the transmission function which minimizes the variance of\nsteady-state currents, for fixed averages, is a collection of boxcar functions.\nThis allows us to show that TURs can be violated by arbitrarily large amounts,\ndepending on the temperature and chemical potential gradients, thus providing\nguidelines to the design of optimal devices.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Jun 2021 16:18:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 21 Jun 2021 14:33:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-06-22"}
